**who —** Sosipatra of Ephesus — a Neoplatonist philosopher and teacher of 4th-century Asia Minor, renowned for her learning and prophetic insight, recorded in Eunapius's Lives of the Philosophers and Sophists

**what —** a Neoplatonist philosopher and teacher of 4th-century Asia Minor, renowned for her learning and prophetic insight, recorded in Eunapius's Lives of the Philosophers and Sophists

**where —** AMP · The Greek Mirror — Rome · Ephesus · Roman Empire (Asia Minor)  Framework inputs: the world's philosophers by year and location; the three classical pillars  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** Rome's female anchor — and the honest seam made plain: the Roman record names almost NO native woman philosopher, and the women philosophers of the Roman era (Sosipatra, Hypatia) worked in the GREEK Neoplatonic tradition. Her seat marks both a real woman and a real silence.

**how —** Seated in the Amphitheater of the World's Philosophers — Anchor Zero, by year and location.

**◌ the mythos —** Rome's female anchor — and the honest seam made plain: the Roman record names almost NO native woman philosopher, and the women philosophers of the Roman era (Sosipatra, Hypatia) worked in the GREEK Neoplatonic tradition. Her seat marks both a real woman and a real silence. an anchor of the Rome house in the amphitheater of philosophers

